Boil a large #pot{} of @water{to taste} with @salt{to taste} for the @dried rigatoni{180%g}.

When boiling, add the rigatoni to the water and bring back to the boil.

Cook until softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pot, off the heat.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to prevent sticking.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Place a large #pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil.

Once the pan is hot, add the @Irish pork mince{250%g} and onion. Fry until pork is browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw mince. Pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Use a #spoon{} to break up the mince as it cooks. Season with salt and @pepper{to taste}.

Stir in the garlic and sprinkle over half the @Italian herbs{1/2%sachet} (double for 4p). Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @Worcester sauce{1%sachet}, @chopped tomatoes with onion & garlic{1%pack} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} (double for 4p) to the pan.

Bring to the boil, stirring, then reduce the heat to medium and simmer until the sauce thickens, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if you feel the sauce is too thick.

When the sauce has reduced, add the @baby spinach{60%g} a handful at a time. Cook until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir the drained pasta, @red wine jus{1%sachet}, a knob of @butter{to taste} and half the @grated cheese{50%g} through the sauce.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Divide the pork pasta between #bowls{}.

Finish with a sprinkle of the remaining cheese.